Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back, folks! The South African team is in a huddle now. The start with the new ball is going to be very crucial. Tom Latham and Will Young are the Kiwi openers. Kagiso Rabada to steam in with three slips and a gully in place. Here we go...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

The pitch appears to be a good one for batting. There is some lateral movement but nothing that falls in the bracket of 'unplayable'. New Zealand have an in-form batting department and they would back themselves. Let's see how South Africa fare with the ball on this surface. Stay tuned...

It was a much-improved batting show by South Africa. They vindicated Dean Elgar's bold decision to bat first and put themselves in a strong position at Stumps on Day 1. Sarel Erwee and Dean Elgar shared a century partnership and the former notched up his maiden Test hundred. The top half of the South African batting got starts and contributed handy runs, however, the middle order failed to capitalize this morning. Matt Henry and Neil Wagner were amazing and led the fightback for the home team. They though will be a little disappointed due to that 9th wicket stand.

The counter-attack from the pair of Keshav Maharaj and Marco Jansen has saved the day for South Africa. They lost the plot completely in the morning session, throwing away the advantage by losing 4 wickets but the 62-run stand for the 9th wicket has helped the touring team to get a decent total in the first innings.

OUT! CAUGHT! That's it! Good bowling from Kyle Jamieson! He sends back the last wicket of South Africa! Shorter one now, around middle and leg at 127.2 kph. Lutho Sipamla ducks under it, but he is not low enough and the ball goes off his gloves and lobs towards second slip. Tim Southee there takes a dolly to dismiss Lutho Sipamla. Marco Jansen is stranded at the other end. South Africa are bowled out for 364!
Commentary.Howout: c Tim Southee b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, outside off. Lutho Sipamla taps it towards point.
Back of a length, outside off. Lutho Sipamla lets that go through.
Good-length delivery, angling in, around middle. Lutho Sipamla works it away towards mid-wicket.
Length ball, outside off. Lutho Sipamla leaves it alone.

Drinks break. New Zealand will take a sigh of relief as they have at last managed to pick up a wicket. Runs were coming thick and fast during the 9th wicket partnership and that has helped South Africa cross the 350-run hurdle. Lutho Sipamla is the last batsman.

OUT! CAUGHT! Kyle Jamieson comes into the attack and strikes! A much-needed breakthrough for New Zealand as this partnership was starting to frustrate them! A shorter ball, outside off at 127.1 kph with extra bounce. Keshav Maharaj hangs back and looks to smash this over gully. But the ball goes off the outside edge and fails to clear the man there. Henry Nicholls stretches to his left and takes a sharp catch. Kyle Jamieson picks up his first wicket and South Africa are now 9 down!
Commentary.Howout: c Henry Nicholls b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: Tom Latham is forced to make a change in bowling. Neil Wagner has been removed and in comes Kyle Jamieson.
Fuller in length, around middle, Keshav Maharaj clears his front foot and drives it towards mid off for a quick single.
Tim Southee drops it short now, around middle. Keshav Maharaj ducks underneath it.
Good-length delivery, around middle and leg. Keshav Maharaj tucks it towards mid-wicket.
FOUR! Keshav Maharaj has raced away to 35 now! On a length this time, outside off. Keshav Maharaj hangs back and slaps this past cover for a cracking boundary.
Another short delivery, on middle. Keshav Maharaj stays in his crease and defends it out.
Back of a length, outside off. Marco Jansen punches it off the back foot towards wide mid off for a single.
Short again, around middle, Keshav Maharaj ducks under it.

FOUR! More runs for Keshav Maharaj and frustration continues for Neil Wagner! Touch short again, around middle, Keshav Maharaj back away and smashes it wide of mid on for yet another boundary. This is an assault on Wagner's strategy to bowl short!
Back of a length, around middle. Keshav Maharaj pulls it towards square leg for a brace.

FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries! That brings up the 50 partnership between these two! A short ball, around middle, Keshav Maharaj clears his front foot and pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a boundary. 350 up for South Africa!
FOUR! Nicely done! Another short ball, outside off. Keshav Maharaj gets on top of the bounce and pushes it over extra cover for a boundary!
Back of a length, around off. Keshav Maharaj hops and defends it out.
Full and angling in on middle, Jansen pushes it towards mid on.
Back of a length, around off, Keshav Maharaj stands tall inside the crease and punches it through covers for three runs.
On a driving length outside off, Keshav allows it through.
Shortish and on middle, defended to the leg side.
Fuller and on off, driven back to the bowler. It flicked Southee's fingers and went on to collide with the stumps at the other end. Marco Jansen was safely in though.
FOUR! This is good positive batting! Short in length, around leg, Maharaj stays back and heaves it over square leg for a boundary.
Tim Southee (30-11-62-1) comes back into the attack now.
Slightly short and on off, Maharaj hops and pushes it in the gap at covers for a single. The stand moves to 35 now.
Short and on off, blocked from the back foot to covers.
On a good length around off, defended to the off side.
Short and around leg, at 130 clicks, Maharaj arches back and tries to ramp it over the keeper but misses. Wagner smiles.
Back of a length, around middle and off, Jansen swivels and swings it over mid-wicket for a single.
A lifter around leg, Jansen defends it in front of square leg.

Fuller and around off, Keshav pushes it to covers and crosses for a run. Henry attacks the ball to his left, slides and has a wayward shy at the keeper's end. Misses and they take another run. Jansen will be on strike!
Uses the angle of the bowler and pushes a length ball to mid on.
Fractionally short and on off, Maharaj is on his toes as he defends it to the off side.
Short and on off, Keshav tries to pull but misses.
Back of a length, around middle and leg, Jansen glances it through square leg for a run.
Full and angling in from around off, Marco blocks it off his front foot.
Predictable length, short and around leg, Jansen turns and pulls it in front of square leg for a single. 11 from the over!
Wagner returns to over the wicket and serves a bouncer on middle at 131 kph, Jansen ducks.
Wagner switches to 'round the wicket and digs it in short, around off, Jansen steers it through backward point for a brace.
FOUR! Jansen is winning this battle. Short in length, around off, Marco Jansen is not backing out, swings his bat and muscles his pull shot over mid-wicket. Wagner smiles.
Some chin music from Neil Wagner! Short and around leg, Jansen is caught in a tangle and leaves uncomfortably. A big stare from Wagner.
FOUR! Bang! Marco Jansen continues to annoy Neil Wagner. Slightly short and around off, Jansen picks it up and powers it over mid-wicket for a boundary.
Slightly short and around middle, angling down at 135.6 kph, Maharaj moves across and tucks it wide of leg gully for two.
Around off, pushed from the back foot to covers.
Digs it in short, around off, Maharaj leans back and leaves.
Sharp short delivery, around off, Maharaj goes down on one knee and tries to pull. He misses as the ball flies over his willow.
Lands it on a length, around off, Maharaj drives it on the up towards mid off.
Around off, the batter has just blocked that from his crease.

EDGY FOUR! More frustration for Wagner and Jansen wins the battle for now. Short in length, around off and angling away, Marco stands back to slap it away but it takes the outside edge and flies over the slip cordon.

Snorter! That's nasty. He has certainly not liked the way Jansen hit him for a boundary. A well-directed bouncer, around leg, Jansen fends it away uncomfortably and it takes the splice. The ball lobs in the air but falls in front of leg gully. Wagner is getting more chirpy now!
Short and around off, angling away, Jansen leans back and evades. Wagner fires a few verbal volleys at Marco.
FOUR! This is some shot, a shot of real intent and ability. Full in length, around middle and off at 128 kph, Jansen decides to go aerial and lofts it over mid on for a boundary.
Short in length and angling away around off, Jansen crouches and lets it be.
Back of a length around off, Jansen blocks it from the back foot.
FOUR! Flashes and flashes hard! Short in length, wide outside off, Maharaj latches onto the room and whacks it past the diving point fielder for a boundary.
This was coming with two men in the deep for the hook shot. Matt Henry bangs it in short, around off, Keshav ducks.
On a good length around off, Maharaj goes on the back foot and defends it to the off side.
Full in length and close to off, Maharaj drives it past the diving bowler to mid off.
Shortish and around off, punched out to the off side.
The batter has just watchfully blocked this out.
The artificial lights are switched off now. The conditions have definitely improved.
Fuller in length around off, Maharaj pushes it in the vacant pocket at covers. He picks up a single to open his account.
Digs it in short, around off, Keshav Maharaj takes his eyes off the ball and ducks awkwardly.
Fuller in length, around off and leaving the batter with the angle, Maharaj is unfazed and lets it be.
A leg gully in place now.
Again the length is short, around middle and leg, Jansen helps it to square leg for one.
Finds the gap! Short in length and on off, Jansen gets on top of the bounce and forces it wide of mid off. Tom Latham chases it down and they take a couple.
Angles across a length ball around off, Jansen drives it off the front foot to mid off.
Slants a length ball on off, Keshav remains on the back foot in defense.
Henry goes short and around off, at 129 clicks, Maharaj ducks at the last moment.
Solid! On a length around off, defended to mid off.
Darts it on a length around off, angling in at 130.1 kph, Maharaj defends it to covers and denies the single.
Almost edges it behind. Matt Henry lands it on a good length outside off, shaping away, Keshav tries to poke inside the line and misses.
Delivers it on a length and outside off, Maharaj defends it off his back foot to cover-point.
Good stop! Angling away from the batter, on a length, Marco Jansen opens the face of his bat and pushes it towards gully where Henry Nicholls makes a fine diving stop.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Beaten this time! Some extra bounce for Wagner. He delivers it short again, around off and angling away, Jansen stays back to punch but misses.
Short and around off, Marco Jansen brings his big frame down as he ducks.
Fuller again, around off, Marco Jansen drives it off his front foot to mid off.
Lands it full and around off, Jansen gets forward and defends it back.
Length ball, outside off. Keshav Maharaj dabs it towards point.
Outside off, on a length. Keshav Maharaj defends it out.
Fuller now, angling in, around middle and off. Keshav Maharaj looks to defend but gets an inside edge on the leg side.
Back of a length, around off. Keshav Maharaj defends it out.
Angling in, around middle, on a length. Marco Jansen pushes it through mid-wicket for a single.
Fuller ball, around middle, Marco Jansen blocks it out.

We're all set to resume. The umpires are back on the field. The Kiwi players get into a huddle near the fence. We have lost no time as it was a quick rain break. Now, all the players are coming out. Keshav Maharaj has joined Marco Jansen. Matt Henry to continue from the other end...
Update 6.30 am IST (1 am GMT) - The rain has effectively stopped and the covers have vanished. The conditions though remain gloomy. We can see that the floodlights are slowly coming on.
Update 6.19 am IST (12.49 am GMT) - Oh, no! It has started to drizzle now and the covers are coming on. The players are leaving the field.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! A superb catch by Daryl Mitchell! Neil Wagner gets his man this time and is one away from a 5-wicket haul! He delivers it on a length, around off, shaping away. Kagiso Rabada leans to block this but gets an outside edge between the keeper and first slip. Tom Blundell lets the ball go but Daryl Mitchell is alert and takes a fine catch diving to his right. To be honest, it was Blundell's catch and credit should go to Mitchell for anticipating it so well. South Africa continue to slip.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: EDGED AND FOUR! On a length, outside off. Kagiso Rabada leans to drive but gets a thick outside edge past the second slip fielder for a boundary. 300 up!
Shorter ball, outside off. Kagiso Rabada blocks it out.
Outside off, on a length. Kagiso Rabada misses as he tries to defend this one.
Tad shorter, around off. Kagiso Rabada just taps it towards point. He was in two minds whether to play it or not.
Angling in, outside off, on a length. Kagiso Rabada gets beaten as he tries to defend this one.
Neil Wagner to continue from the opposite end...
Good-length delivery, outside off, shaping away. Marco Jansen leaves it alone.
Another full ball, around the off pole. Marco Jansen blocks it out once again.
Fuller now, outside off. Marco Jansen leans and defends it out.
On a length, around middle. Marco Jansen dabs it out towards cover.
Beauty! On a length, around off, shaping away just a tad. Marco Jansen looks to defend this but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller ball, outside off. Marco Jansen drives it towards mid off.
We are back! The players stride out to the middle for the afternoon session. It's going to be Matt Henry to bowl the first over. Here we go...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

The Kiwis have done well to make a comeback in this Test match but it's still not over. They will have to pick the remaining wickets without giving away many runs. It would be a great achievement for them if they restrict South Africa under 325 after what transpired on Day 1. Can they do it or will the South African lower order put up a stern resistance? Do join us at 6.10 am IST (12.40 am GMT) to find out.

Four wickets in the session and New Zealand stamped their authority this morning! Gaining the upper hand is one thing and maintaining it is another. South Africa enjoyed a great Day 1 but weren't as good in the morning session of Day 2. They surrendered the advantage and wasted a good opportunity to bat New Zealand out of this Test match. Temba Bavuma was cleaned up by Matt Henry and soon after that, Kyle Verreynne's unconvincing stay at the crease was ended by the same bowler. After getting dropped twice, on 7 last evening and on 21 this morning, Rassie van der Dussen eventually ran out of luck and was dismissed while chasing a wide delivery.
Length, outside off. Kagiso Rabada stays back and looks to block this, but the ball goes off the outside edge and falls short of the fielder at gully. That will be Lunch on Day 2!
Last ball of the morning session coming up...
Much fuller, outside off. Kagiso Rabada leans and pushes it past mid off for a couple of runs.
Neil Wagner drops it short now, around middle. Kagiso Rabada ducks under it.
Tad fuller, around off. Kagiso Rabada pushes it towards mid off.
Good-length delivery, outside off, shaping away. Kagiso Rabada stays in his crease and looks to defend this but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Angling in, around middle and leg, on a length. Kagiso Rabada taps it towards mid-wicket.
Length ball, around middle. Marco Jansen blocks it out.
Edged and just short of the second slip fielder! A fuller ball, outside off. Marco Jansen leans and looks to defend, but gets an outside edge, towards second slip, who collects it on the bounce.
Good-length delivery, around middle, Marco Jansen knocks it towards mid on.
Back of a length, outside off. Marco Jansen leaves it alone.
Outside off, on a length. Marco Jansen dabs it towards point.
Length, around middle. Marco Jansen defends it out solidly.
On a length, around middle. Kagiso Rabada pushes it back to the bowler.
Fuller, down the leg side. Kagiso Rabada leaves it alone.
Kagiso Rabada comes out to bat next ahead of Keshav Maharaj.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! A good comeback by Neil Wagner! He strikes and gets rid of Wiaan Mulder, who was looking assured at the crease. Short in length on middle, Wiaan Mulder stays in his crease and looks to pull this but he is way too early into his shot as the ball arrives late. It flies high towards the keeper off the top edge and Tom Blundell immediately calls for it. He grabs the skier safely and New Zealand lose their seventh wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Wow, wonderful shot! Tad shorter now, outside off. Wiaan Mulder stays in his crease, gets on his toes and punches it through the gap at covers for a boundary.
On a length, outside off. Wiaan Mulder lets that go through.
It has turned overcast out there. A few drops of rain can be seen but nothing serious.
Tad fuller, outside off. Wiaan Mulder leans and blocks it out.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Second boundary of the over! Kyle Jamieson pitches this one up, around off. Marco Jansen leans and pushes it past mid off for a boundary.
This one lands on a length, outside off. Marco Jansen offers no shot.
Touch fuller, on middle. Marco Jansen leans and blocks it out solidly.
Length, around off. Marco Jansen stays in his crease and blocks it out.
FOUR! Easy pickings! On a length, darting it on the pads. Marco Jansen flicks it towards fine leg for a boundary.
Good start! Touch shorter, outside off, this one nips away after landing. Marco Jansen looks to defend this but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Kyle Jamieson is back on. 0/66 in his 24 overs so far.
Shaping away, outside off, on a length. Wiaan Mulder shoulders his arms at it.
Fuller now, around off. Wiaan Mulder presses forward and blocks it out.
Length, around off. Wiaan Mulder defends it out.
An appeal for LBW, but turned down! On a length, darting it on the pads. Wiaan Mulder looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad. That was pitching outside leg.
Back of a length, outside off, shaping away. Wiaan Mulder looks to defend this but misses.
Fuller ball, outside off. Marco Jansen leans and drives it past cover. Three taken!
Angling in, around middle and on a length. Wiaan Mulder pushes it towards mid-wicket.
Length, outside off. Wiaan Mulder leaves it alone.

FOUR! Beautiful shot! Full again, around middle, Wiaan Mulder presents the full face of the bat and drives it past mid on for a boundary. South Africa need more of these! Just the third boundary of the day.
Angling in, around middle and leg, on a length. Wiaan Mulder taps it towards mid-wicket.
Tad fuller now, around off, shaping in a bit. Wiaan Mulder leans and defends it out.
Length, on middle. Wiaan Mulder blocks it out solidly.
Good-length delivery, outside off, shaping away, at 130.4 clicks. Marco Jansen leaves it alone.
Beaten! Outside off, on a length. Marco Jansen looks to defend but gets beaten.
Neil Wagner drops it short now, around middle. Marco Jansen ducks underneath it.
Marco Jansen, the tall man, is the new batter.

OUT! CAUGHT! Oh, dear! A wicket in an unusual manner! Neil Wagner cannot believe it himself and has a sheepish smile on his face! But New Zealand will take that! A yorker-length delivery, wide of off at 126.3 kph. Rassie van der Dussen reaches out and tries to squeeze it away but the ball goes off the outside edge towards first slip. Daryl Mitchell there pouches it safely. The umpires want to check it for the bump ball but the replays show that it has clearly gone off the outside edge to the fielder. Rassie van der Dussen runs out of his luck eventually - was dropped on 7 and 21.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: This one comes back in a tad, on middle and on a length. Rassie van der Dussen defends it out.
On a length, shaping away, outside off. Rassie van der Dussen leaves it alone.
On a length and around middle, Rassie stays back and wrists it behind square leg for a run.
Around middle and off, angling in, Rassie van der Dussen works it on the leg side and finds the fielder standing in front of square on the leg side.
Fuller and closer to off, moving back in, Rassie gets behind the line, covers the movement and pushes it towards mid on.
Lands it on a length and close to off, Rassie stays on the back foot and defends it to the off side.
Digs it in short on middle, Mulder stands back and pulls it behind square leg for a single.
Sliding down the leg side, on a length, Wiaan gets across and then shoulders arms.
Delivers it on a length around middle, it's defended from the back foot to the leg side. Maiden.
Better delivery. Full and around off, shaping back into middle and off, Rassie van der Dussen hops on the back foot and defends it to the leg side.
Full and way wide outside off, left alone.
Around off, on a length and angling away, Rassie plays at it gently and pushes it to point.
Back of a length, on top of off, Rassie van der Dussen goes on his toes and plays it down to cover-point.
A gentle loosener from Neil Wagner. Serves it a touch short and wide outside off, Rassie allows it through to the keeper.
Neil Wagner (19-7-50-1) comes into the attack now.
Around off, on a length, Wiaan stays on the back foot and blocks it safely.
On a length and around off, shaping away, Wiaan Mulder hangs back and decides to play at it at the last moment. He brings his bat down and guides it past gully for a couple of runs.
Southee tries to repeat the last delivery from middle and leg. But it lands and skid on with the angle. Mulder helps it off his pads to square leg.
Southee serves it full and just outside off, nipping away, Mulder covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Full and around leg, it's worked off the pads to deep square leg for a single.
In the region outside off, van der Dussen allows it through to the keeper.
Extra bounce. Back of a length and around off, Wiaan Mulder initially looks to commit himself into the shot but then withdraws his bat.
An attempted inswinger but the line starts from way wide outside off. Wiaan Mulder has nothing to do with it.
Fuller and on off, darting in, Mulder defends it solidly to the off side.
Action replay of the previous delivery. Wiaan has looked a lot assured at the crease.
On a length and outside off, left alone.

Risky single! Fuller and on off, angling in, Rassie pushes it in front of Wagner at mid-wicket and scampers across to the other end. Neil has a shy at the striker's end but misses. Probably, a better opportunity was at the bowler's end.
Fuller in length and on off, angling in, Wiaan Mulder gets forward to cover the line and blocks it safely.
In the corridor of uncertainty, that is left alone for the keeper to collect.
This one is on a length and around off, shaping away, Mulder shoulders arms.
Fullish and on off, Wiaan gently works it across the line to mid-wicket.
An outswinger in the channel outside off, Wiaan allows it through to the keeper.

My word, that's an interesting shot selection from Mulder. A delivery around middle and leg, angling down, Wiaan Mulder walks forward and across the stumps, exposing two stumps and attempting to flick but misses.
Tim Southee (26-10-53-1) is back into the attack.
Kyle Jamieson goes wide of the crease and delivers it on a good length outside off. The ball lands and holds its line as Rassie shoulders arms.
On a length, around off and angling in, Rassie defends it from the crease to mid-wicket.
Angling in from a fuller length around off, van der Dussen defends it towards mid on.

FOUR! Finds the fence! This time it's too full and too straight from Kyle Jamieson, Rassie van der Dussen leans across and flicks it wide of the square leg fielder. It races through and has enough legs to touch the boundary line.
Stays on the back foot to a delivery around middle and works it with the angle to square leg. Not in the gap though.
Bowls it on a length and around off, Rassie defends it from the back foot to the leg side.

DRINKS! An hour that has completely belonged to the hosts! They have been top-notch with their bowling and have been rewarded with the wickets of Temba Bavuma and Kyle Verreynne. The pressure is on South Africa for now, and they will need a partnership from here to get them to a big total.
Taps a length ball to covers and scampers across to the other end.
Fuller in length and outside off, could have been left out, but Rassie is very nervous, he gets forward and pushes it to covers.
Around off, on a length, defended to the off side.
Lands it on a length, close to off, Rassie van der Dussen defends it from the upper half of his bat. He is looking very tentative against Henry.
Plenty of 3s this morning. Full and around off, angling in, Mulder clips it through mid-wicket for three runs.
Fullish and on middle, defended back to the bowler.

Miscommunication but no harm is done. Kyle Jamieson delivers a length ball on middle and leg, Rassie nudges it down to fine leg and takes a single. He wants the second run too and rushes for it. His partner though realizes late and then sets off. The throw comes to the wrong end, i.e. the keeper's end and that allows Wiaan time to race towards the other end.
Fuller and just outside off, Rassie van der Dussen takes his front leg forward, has a close look at it and then shoulders arms.
Fraction short in length and wide outside off, Rassie van der Dussen lets it be.
On a driving length outside off, Rassie is very watchful at the moment. He just watches the line and allows it through.
This one is on a length and outside off, angling in, Rassie van der Dussen stays inside the crease to cover the line and shoulders arms.
Movement there for Jamieson but his line is wide outside off, Rassie van der Dussen has an easy leave.
Serves it on a length around off, straightening a hint off the seam Wiaan goes on the back foot and defends it from the outer half of his blade. Third maiden in a row!
Fuller again, around off, Mulder defends it to the off side
Fuller and around off, shaping in, Mulder presses forward confidently and defends it right under his eyes. Solid.
Around off, on a length, Wiaan gets opened up in his stance as he defends it to the off side.
This one nips back in from a length outside off, Mulder decides to make a leave this time.
Well bowled! Matt Henry keeps his line close to off, shaping away, Mulder feels for it and is beaten.
Full and wide outside off, another leave from Rassie van der Dussen to round off the over. A maiden!
In the channel outside off, quite wide again to bother the batsman who allows it through.
This one is quite wide outside off, shaping away, Rassie has an easy leave this time.
Beaten! Fuller in length and closer to off, Rassie van der Dussen tries to defend the line but gets beaten by the away movement.
On a length and close to off, Rassie van der Dussen defends it from the back foot.
Starts with a full delivery, around off, Rassie defends it on the leg side.
A beauty to end the over! On a length again, outside off. Wiaan Mulder stays in his crease and looks to defend but misses. Another successful over by Matt Henry, a wicket maiden!
Length ball, around middle, Wiaan Mulder blocks it out solidly.
Wiaan Mulder is the new batter.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIPS! Matt Henry has his second wicket of the morning and is impressing one and all once again. He delivers it on a length outside off, at 133.5 kph, getting it to nip away after landing. Kyle Verreynne, who looked uncomfortable throughout his stay, lunges forward to defend with his bat hanging away from the body. He doesn't account for the movement and ends up edging it to Tom Latham at second slip. He makes no mistake and it's turning out to be a fabulous morning for the home side.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Matt Henry

Commentary.Commentary: Another appeal for LBW, but the umpire turns it down! Another length ball, nipping back in, around middle and leg. Kyle Verreynne looks to flick but misses. That was probably sliding down leg too.
Length, outside off. Kyle Verreynne defends it out.
Beaten! Tad fuller, outside off, shaping away. Kyle Verreynne looks to drive this away from his body and gets beaten!
Length ball, around middle. Rassie van der Dussen closes the face of his bat and tucks it towards square leg.

An appeal for LBW, but the umpire says no! Fuller ball, nipping back in around middle and leg. Rassie van der Dussen looks to flick, but misses and gtes hit on his pads. That was definitely sliding down leg.
Tad shorter, outside off. Rassie van der Dussen leaves it alone.
Back of a length, outside off. Rassie van der Dussen shoulders his arms at it.
Good shot! Fuller now, jagging back in around middle, Kyle Verreynne flicks it past mid-wicket. Three taken!
Good-length delivery, shaping away, outside off. Kyle Verreynne leaves it alone.
On a length, around off. Rassie van der Dussen blocks it out. End of a successful over by Matt Henry!

OUT! KNOCKED HIM OVER! This is just what New Zealand wanted! Matt Henry decides to do it all by himself with the catches going down off his bowling. A terrific change in length from him. Hurls across a fantastic yorker, at 132.6 kph, it's going dead straight with the angle, no swing whatsoever on it. Temba Bavuma is a shade early into his shot as the ball dips in front of his bat. It sneaks past the bottom edge and disturbs the off pole. Bavuma's stay is over and New Zealand have their first breakthrough on Day 2.
Commentary.Howout: b Matt Henry

Yet another beautiful day at the Hagley Oval. The hosts, who usually dominate proceedings at this venue, are a bit under the pump. This morning session holds great importance as they would like to steal the momentum. The second new ball is only 10 overs old and combined with the early morning conditions, the Kiwi bowlers can cause trouble. For South Africa, it's all about holding the advantage and not giving it away. Day 1 is done and it's a fresh day, so they cannot rest on their laurels. We're minutes away now. The players are taking the field.

The Proteas are in a commanding position, Temba Bavuma and Rassie van der Dussen are the two batters at the crease. They were troubled initially by the bowlers but they have done exceptionally well to survive till the end of the day. New Zealand did take the second new ball immediately but they were not rewarded with the same, things will only get difficult for them, and they will want to grab early wickets and not let the visitors get away with a big total. The second new ball is only 10 overs old, and a few wickets in the first session will bring New Zealand back in the game.

Welcome back, folks! It’s time for Day 2 of this exciting Test. We saw Day 1 being dominated by South Africa. Many were shocked after Dean Elgar chose to bat. But, you know what they say, fortune favors the brave. The batters lived up to the expectations and put a great batting performance. Sarel Erwee notched up his maiden ton, while Elgar and Aiden Markram also played fine knocks. The hosts did pull things back together in the final session, but they will want to capitalize on the same and not let the batters build another partnership.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

That's a wrap to the first day's play. For a change, New Zealand had to toil hard at the Hagley Oval and would have to come up with a better show on Day 2. South Africa, unexpectedly, have gained the upper hand and they will aim to bat once and bat big. Will they succeed? Do join us to find out. The first ball will be at 3.30 am IST (10 pm GMT, previous day) but as usual, our build-up will begin in advance. Until then, it's goodbye and cheers!

New Zealand didn't bowl badly. They were just countered well with discipline by the Saffas. There was some adjustment visible in the technique of the South African batters. In the first Test, they played at too many deliveries meant to be left alone. The tourists addressed that and their batters looked more assured at the crease. Massive credit goes to Sarel Erwee who had a debut to forget but showed character to bounce back and register his maiden Test ton. Aiden Markram too, who has his Test spot under the scanner, played a responsible hand and was involved in an 88-run stand to keep the Kiwis at bay in the afternoon.

'Really?' That's the expression most of us had when Dean Elgar elected to bat. Given how their batting flopped in the first Test, it was a gutsy and bold decision. 'It's important for us to front up...' this is what Dean Elgar stated at the toss and he led from the front. A wicket-less first session, a century stand for the opening wicket - South Africa's first away from home in 10 years and 34 Tests - and the touring team vindicated its skipper's decision.

A session that finally brought some success for the Kiwis! They managed to remove both the set batters in Aiden Markram and Sarel Erwee and it would have been even better had Will Young not dropped Rassie van der Dussen. Even Temba Bavuma had a shaky start but survived the nervy period as a couple of edges evaded the slip cordon. All in all, with a bit of luck, New Zealand could have managed to end the day's play more brightly.
Full in length around middle, angling in, Rassie flicks it off his pads to mid-wicket. That will be it - Stumps on Day 1!
Delivers it on a length, around off and shooting off the surface, Rassie van der Dussen tries to defend but gets hit on the splice.
Is that a run out?

NOT OUT! Fuller and around off, Rassie van der Dussen gets on the front foot and scuffs his drive off the inner half to mid on. He steps out for a run but Bavuma has turned his back on him. The fielder there dives and parries it to mid off who fires a direct hit at the striker's end. New Zealand appeal, it's referred upstairs but the replays find that Rassie is easily home.
In the channel outside off, Rassie offers no shot.
Lands it on a length and around off, Rassie van der Dussen gets across the stumps a bit and defends it near his body.

He is pinged on the pads, they appeal but the finger stays down. Southee is pretty confident that he has trapped Bavuma in front. Tom Latham gets convinced and he takes the referral. The Ball Tracking shows that it's heading over the stumps. One review is wasted.

On a length, around middle. Rassie van der Dussen is taken by surprise due to the extra bounce, but he does well to get some bat on it as he blocks.
Matt Henry to share the second new cherry from the other end.

Wagner oversteps and delivers a full ball down the leg side, Rassie fails to flick and it goes off his pads to fine leg. They take a couple of leg byes.
Bouncer around middle and leg, Rassie van der Dussen ducks underneath it.

DRINKS! An exciting first hour of the final session! The hosts have managed to pull things back and have got rid of the two set batters. They are making it difficult for the new batters to settle in and keeping things tight. The second new ball is just a few overs away now, and Temba Bavuma and Rassie van der Dussen will be hoping they survive till the end of the day. Also, Kyle Jamieson (17-6-48-0) comes back to bowl.

Matt Henry hurls across a length ball, outside off and angling away, Sarel Erwee tries driving away from his body but all he manages is a thick outside edge. A simple catch for Tom Blundell and that ends a fantastic knock. The hosts are roaring now and have two new batters at the crease. The second new ball is also not far away.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Matt Henry

Daryl Mitchell there pouches it safely. South Africa lose their second wicket after an 88-run stand!
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Neil Wagner

Length ball, around off. Sarel Erwee defends it out off the back foot.

On a length, around middle. Sarel Erwee blocks it out.

Back for the final session. The ground is bathed in sunshine and the conditions are looking extremely good for batting. South Africa have done a great job thus far and would love to keep the advantage on their side by playing out the remaining 32 overs without any hiccups. Tim Southee to open proceedings with the ball. Two slips and a gully in place...

The hosts have bowled well, but they have just not been able to pick wickets. They started off the session well, by picking up the wicket of the South African skipper, thanks to a peach of a delivery by Tim Southee. But since then, it's been only South Africa! Neil Wagner did test Sarel Erwee with all his short deliveries, but could not get any reward for the same. The pitch is only getting easy to bat on and it will be tough for New Zealand to grab wickets in the final session of the day. Do join us at 8.30 am IST (3 am GMT) for the next segment.

Another session that belonged to the visitors, courtesy of some fine batting! South Africa are moving along nicely. They have made the New Zealand bowlers work really hard and have not given it away. After losing Dean Elgar early in the session, Aiden Markram and Sarel Erwee have built another good partnership. Sarel Erwee has looked nothing but elegant. He has respected the good balls and put away the bad ones, and scored his maiden Test century just in his second Test. While, Aiden Markram who has not been at his best in the recent past, is also being patient there and proving his worth.
On a good length around middle, Sarel Erwee defends it solidly to end the over and this session. Tea on Day 1!
Sliding down the leg side, Sarel lets it be.
Too full in length, around off, Sarel defends it to the off side.

FOUR! HUNDRED FOR ERWEE! His first in Tests and it's been a terrific knock! Short in length, around middle and nicely sitting up for the batter, Sarel rides the bounce and pulls it in the gap at square leg for a boundary. It's been a responsible and highly skilful knock. Very challenging at the start but he weathered the storm and now has a century to his name. The helmet comes off and he raises his arms in celebration. Your first hundred will always have a special place in your heart. Meanwhile, the 50-run stand has also come up.
Short again, down the leg side, Sarel shoulders arms.
Bouncer around leg, Sarel ducks.
Just enough time to squeeze another over.
Short leg in place now.... This will be the last over before Tea.
Full and angling in around off, Aiden is forward in defense.
Darts it in full, around off, Aiden defends it off his front foot.
Good leave. This time Colin de Grandhomme delivers it on a length and just outside off, it holds its line and Markram shoulders arms.
Bowls an outswinger, on a length and outside off, Aiden shoulders arms.
Puts it on a fuller length around off, angling in and straightening, Markram defends it near his front pad.
Full and wide outside off, swinging in the air, Markram drives it off his front foot to covers.

Switches to 'round the wicket and angles in a length ball around off, Markram uses the crease and turns it in the gap at mid-wicket. He takes a single, turns for the second run but it's not available.
Pitches it up and around off, angling away again, Aiden Markram drives it square of the wicket on the off side. Finds point.
Good length, on off, defended off the back foot to the off side.
Bowls it on a length and outside off, it's left alone.
FOUR! Lovely shot! A touch short and around leg, Aiden Markram goes on the back foot and glances it through square leg for a lovely boundary.
Delivers it on a length and outside off, angling away, Markram allows it through to the keeper.
Moves to 96! Angling into the left-hander, Sarel Erwee uses the angle to his advantage and tucks it through mid-wicket for a brace.
Fuller and off, defended to the off side.
Serves another delivery in the channel outside off, testing the patience of a batsman on 94, Erwee allows it through once more.
A gentle delivery, on a length and outside off, angling in, Sarel Erwee allows it through.
Good length and close to off, angling in, Sarel defends it from the back foot.
The batter has just blocked that from his crease.
FOUR! Good timing! Aiden Markram receives a full ball in his half, around middle and flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary. 150 comes up!
Ticks off from 93 with a single. Short and around leg,it's worked down to fine leg.

THAT'S A SNORTER! Sarel Erwee takes his eyes off the ball and suffers a blow on his elbow. Neil Wagner bangs it in short, around middle, Erwee is taken by surprise as he attempts to sways away. Fails to do so and is hit on the elbow.

Slightly short and around off, Aiden sticks on the back foot in defense.
Pitches it up and outside off, Aiden drives but finds the fielder at covers.
Angles in a length ball on off, Erwee defends it from the back foot. Another maiden, 5 in a row. Just a leg bye during this period.
Full and around off, angling in, Sarel defends it back.
The batter has just blocked that from his crease.
Late movement. Colin de Grandhomme feeds it on a length around middle and leg, Sarel Erwee tries to work it on the leg side but misses and is hit on the back leg.
Lands it on a length and outside off, it's defended off the back foot to covers.
Delivers it on a length around off, Sarel Erwee goes on the back foot and defends. He stays on 93.
On a good length around middle, shaping in, Markram goes firmly on the back foot in defense.
From over the wicket, a length ball is angled across the batter, Markram pushes it to point.
Darts in a short ball around leg, at 132 kph, Erwee fails to glance and it flies past Southee at leg gully for a leg bye.
Digs it in short again, around middle and leg, Sarel Erwee jumps and taps it down to short leg.
Short and down the leg side, left alone with ease.
Wagner continues with his plan from 'round the wicket. Hurls across a delivery on the shorter side around leg, Sarel tucks it to square leg.
Angling in around off, on a length and straightening off the seam, Markram stays on the back foot and defends it down.
The batter shoulders arms to let that one through.
Very full and on middle, Markram pushes it down to mid on.
Back of a length, on top of off, Aiden is on his toes as he defends.
Another outswinger, in the channel outside off, Markram has nothing to do with it.
Nice shape for Colin de Grandhomme. Lands it full and close to off, shaping away, Aiden makes a watchful leave.
Colin de Grandhomme is getting ready to bowl now. 4-0-14-0 are his figures so far.
Neil Wagner ends with a short ball again, down the leg side. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
Short again, around middle. Sarel Erwee ducks and lets it go.

Back of a length, around middle and leg. Sarel Erwee stays in his crease and taps it towards mid-wicket.
Neil Wagner drops it short now, around middle and leg. Sarel Erwee ducks under it.
Shorter ball, spraying it down the leg side. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.

Shorter ball, around middle. Aiden Markram pushes it back to the bowler.
Touch shorter, around off. Aiden Markram gets an inside edge onto his pads while trying to defend.
On a length, outside off. Aiden Markram pushes this away towards mid off.

On a length, outside off. Aiden Markram defends it out.

Outside off, on a length. Aiden Markram offers no shot on that!
Much fuller now, outside off. Aiden Markram drives with the outer half of his bat towards cover-point.
Fraction short again, around off. Aiden Markram presents the full face of the bat and defends it out.
Back of a length, outside off. Aiden Markram leaves it alone.

Length, around off. Aiden Markram defends it out.

Touch short, outside off. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
An inswinger, on a length, around middle, Sarel Erwee taps it towards mid-wicket.
Back of a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee will watch it sail through to the keeper.
Length, outside off. Sarel Erwee offers no shot on that.
Overpitches this one, around off. Aiden Markram drives but finds the fielder at covers who stops the ball with a dive.
On a length, outside off. Aiden Markram leans and defends it out.
Short again, around middle, Sarel Erwee miscues his pull towards square leg for a single.

Length, around middle and leg. Aiden Markram nudges it to mid-wicket.

South Africa have got the platform to capitalize whereas New Zealand have an opening to pick up more wickets. The pitch has not flattened out much and we can still see some seam movement. A crucial next hour coming up. Who will pocket the upper hand?
Fuller again, around middle, Sarel Erwee closes the face of his bat and tucks it towards mid-wicket for a single.

OUT! BOWLED! What a sight for a fast bowler! Hitting the top of off and Nelson strikes! This is beautiful from Tim Southee. He speeds in from 'round the wicket and delivers it close to off on a good length. The angle takes it into the batter, Elgar tries to defend but is squared up as the ball nips away a shade to beat the outside edge of his bat. It goes on to tickle the top of the off stump and New Zealand have finally managed to get a breakthrough. The century stand is over and Tim Southee has 50 Test wickets at the Hagley Oval.

We're back! The players have returned to the field for the afternoon session. It's going to be Kyle Jamieson to bowl the first over. Here we go...

We cannot fault New Zealand for not trying. They stuck to good lines and lengths but didn't get the same kind of response from the pitch that they got in the first Test. It's looking a lot better for batting although there is some gentle movement on offer. The surface is only going to get better for batting in the afternoon and the hosts will have to switch to 'Plan B' if they don't get success immediately after the break. Do join us at 6.10 am IST (12.40 am GMT) for the second session.

Two hours of steel and resolve! 'It's important for us to front up...' this is what Dean Elgar stated at the toss after taking a bold decision to bat first. His decision has been vindicated. It doesn't matter how many runs you get in the first session of a Test match when the main focus is survival. Still, South Africa have notched up 80 runs and Sarel Erwee, in particular, looked a lot at ease with his technique and brought up his maiden Test fifty. Dean Elgar, as usual, has accumulated balls and played his role in the opening partnership.

Touch fuller, around middle, Dean Elgar shows the full face of the bat and taps it past mid on for a brace.
Here comes Neil Wagner...
Well bowled! Tad shorter, outside off. Sarel Erwee looks to have a poke at it but gets beaten.
FOUR! Glorious! Pitches this one up, outside off. Sarel Erwee leans and drives it past cover for a beautiful boundary.
Full now, outside off. Sarel Erwee pushes it towards mid off.
On a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee taps it towards point.
Full again, an inswinger, around middle. Sarel Erwee tucks it towards mid-wicket. Neil Wagner there dives to his left and does well to stop the ball.
Colin de Grandhomme begins with a fuller ball, nipping back in, on middle. Sarel Erwee pushes it towards mid on.
As expected, Colin de Grandhomme is brought into the attack ahead of Wagner. Three slips and a gully in place...
Angling it in, on a good length, around off. Dean Elgar blocks it out.
Extra bounce! A tad shorter, around middle, Dean Elgar does well to get his glove on it and keep it away.
Kyle Jamieson drops it short now, outside off, at 127.7 kph. Dean Elgar stays in his crease and blocks it out.
Colin de Grandhomme is seen warming up. Will he come on to bowl before Neil Wagner?
Good-length delivery, angling it in on middle. Dean Elgar tucks it towards square leg.
Back of a length again, outside off. Dean Elgar offers no shot on that.
Kyle Jamieson serves a shorter ball from 'round the wicket, outside off, at 126.6 clicks. Dean Elgar lets that go through.
On a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
Much fuller now, outside off. Dean Elgar drives, but he gets an inside edge onto his pads. The ball rolls towards covers and the batters cross ends.
Back of a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee hops and taps it towards cover for a quick single.
The physio comes out. Not much that he can do here. Sarel Erwee is doing some stretching to ease the pain. The Kiwi players are seen smiling.
Ouch! A shorter ball, around middle, Sarel Erwee looks to tuck this away but he misses and gets hit on the groin area. Sarel Erwee seems to be in some pain here.
On a length now, around middle and leg. Dean Elgar tucks it towards square leg for a single.
Fuller ball, outside off. Dean Elgar looks to drive but gets an outside edge towards gully.
Uses the angle of the bowler and nudges it behind square leg for a couple of runs.
Around off, on a length, blocked off the front foot.

FOUR! Glorious! Fuller in length and outside off, at 128.5 kph, Sarel Erwee nicely leans into the drive and thumps it down the ground for a boundary at long off. The 50-run stand comes up and this is the first for the opening wicket for them in 16 innings, informs the on-air commentator.
Fractionally short and on off, Erwee goes back and defends it towards cover-point.
A gentle outswinger outside off, at 128.5 kph, Sarel Erwee watches it closely before making a leave.
Full and around off, angling in, Sarel is on the front foot and defends it back with a straight bat.
Short in length on middle, it's pulled in control by Erwee as he sends it to deep square leg for a single.
Bouncer and on middle, Sarel Erwee ducks.

FOUR! Streaky! Henry goes short with his length, outside off at 132 kph, Erwee goes on his toes to cut it through the line but it takes the inner edge, beats the stumps and scoots away to the fine leg fence.
In the zone outside off, left alone.

Well left! Back of a length, around off and shaping in a bit, Sarel Erwee offers no shot. The ball though keeps on swerving to the right of the keeper and Tom Blundell once again makes a great stop behind the stumps.
Delivers it on a length around leg, at 139 kph, Erwee stays back to work it on the leg side but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
Fullish and outside off, it lands and moves away a shade, Elgar has nothing to offer.
Angling in from around off, the batter has just blocked that from his crease.
Around off, on a length and angling in, Elgar covers the line and offers a straight bat in defense.
Almost drags it on! Fuller in length and outside off, at 127 clicks, Dean Elgar tries to drive away from his body but gets a big inside edge onto the pads.
Short in length and outside off, Elgar gets across to guard his stumps and then shoulders arms.
The line is straight from Kyle Jamieson. Elgar tucks it on the leg side but finds the fielder in front of square leg.
On middle, turned on the leg side but straight to mid-wicket.
FOUR! That's a good shot! Full in length around middle and leg, Sarel Erwee leans across and flicks it firmly through backward square leg for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone.
Angling down the leg side, it's tucked behind square leg for a couple of runs.
Matt Henry gets a bit closer to the stumps, on a length and again it's moving back in, Sarel Erwee lets it be. Tom Blundell does well to collect it with a dive.
On a length and outside off, shaping back in a little, Sarel Erwee has nothing to do with it.
Puts it on a fuller length around off, Dean Elgar is on the front foot as he defends it to covers.
Digs it in short, around leg, Sarel Erwee stands back and pulls it to fine leg for a single.
That's a risky shot! Jamieson delivers it on a fuller length and forces the batsman to have a go at it. Erwee drives it through covers for a couple of runs.
Keeps it full and around off, getting it to seam away from the left-hander, Erwee covers the line and allows it through to the keeper.
In the channel outside off, on a good length and angling away, Sarel lets it through to the keeper.
Darts it in, very full and around off, Sarel Erwee digs it out to the off side.

DRINKS! A solid first hour for South Africa! Both Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee have looked good in the middle and are batting with some positive intent! New Zealand have not created a lot of chances so far, but they will be eager to get their first wicket before Lunch.
Sharp movement. Henry brings a length ball back into the batsman from around off, Elgar has his bat down in time as he keeps it out to square leg.
Identical to the last delivery, once again Elgar covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Back of a length and outside off, Dean shoulders arms.
Lands it on a length and outside off, Sarel drives it square of the wicket on the off side for another three runs in this over. Showing more intent which was lacking in the first Test.
In the channel outside off, Erwee allows it through to the keeper.

IN THE AIR... Elgar's heart would have been in his mouth. Fuller and outside off, a loose drive from Elgar, away from his body and he chips it past the diving point fielder. Three runs are taken. Elgar knows that was not a great shot.
Matt Henry (4-0-8-0) comes back to bowl.
Pitches it up and around off, it's defended watchfully to the off side.

FOUR! Here comes the first boundary for Sarel Erwee. Short in length and outside off, leaving the batter with the angle, Sarel goes on his toes and steers it with a straight bat through point for a boundary. Kyle Jamieson won't mind that shot as he went with a straight bat and there was every chance of an outside edge.
Serves it on a length around leg, Sarel tries to work it on the leg side but perhaps gets some inside edge onto the pads.
Very full and on middle, at 129.7 kph, Sarel Erwee brings his bat down in time and keeps it out to mid-wicket.
This one is pitched just ahead of a length around off, Elgar draws forward and pushes it with gentle hands to covers for a quick run.
That's a beauty! Kyle Jamieson speeds in from 'round the wicket and angles in a length ball close to off. Elgar stays back to play the line but it nips away to beat his bat.
Full in length and on off, shaping back in, Sarel Erwee is on the front foot and drives it off the inner half to mid on.
Too full and close to off, Sarel drives it through the line but finds mid off.
Fuller in length and around off, Sarel Erwee drives it down the ground and beats the diving mid on fielder. Collects a couple.
Southee attempts for an inswinger but it goes down the leg side, Sarel Erwee tries to buy some cheap runs but fails to connect with his attempted flick shot.
In the channel outside off, shaping away, Sarel Erwee allows it through to the keeper.
Fuller in length and around middle, Sarel Erwee defends it watchfully from the crease. Looking more assured than he was in his debut Test.
Got 'em! Gone! Not really. Sarel Erwee was not ready and pulls out. Tim Southee though keeps running and delivers. Strikes the stumps and has a big smile on his face.
Serves it on a length, around off and shaping away with the seam movement, Elgar covers the line and shoulders arms. Another maiden for Kyle!
Goes full and on middle, this time Elgar uses his bat and wrists it towards square leg.

Excellent delivery from Jamieson. Great variation. After bowling a few outswingers, he brings one back in. It though has too much height on it and strikes Elgar high on the pads who has offered no shot.
Delivers it on a good length around off at 130.7 kph, some extra bounce, Elgar deals with it well and defends it down towards square leg.
Very full in length and outside off, at 130.6 kph, Elgar defends it towards covers.
Shaping away from the left-hander, pitching on middle and leg, Elgar offers no shot.
On a length and around off, Sarel is solidly behind the line in defense.
Pitches it up and outside off, Erwee drives it softly to cover-point.
Around off, fuller in length and nipping in, it's defended safely on the leg side. Southee is eyeing those pads.

Oohhh...that was not too far away from the leg pole. This is an inswinging fuller delivery, around leg and shaping down, Sarel Erwee fails to flick and Tom Blundell dives full length to his right to collect the ball.
Southee returns to over the wicket for Sarel Erwee. Serves it full and on the driving length outside off, Sarel has nothing to do with it.
Southee delivers a length ball on the pads, Elgar nudges it to fine leg and picks up a single.
Back of a length, this one comes in a tad, down the leg side, at 133.3 clicks. Sarel Erwee looks to flick but misses.
Short again, shaping away, outside off. Sarel Erwee lets that go through to the keeper.
Fraction short, around off. Sarel Erwee presents the full face of his bat and defends it out.
Back of a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee taps it towards point off the back foot.
An outswinger, on a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee offers no shot on that.
Kyle Jamieson starts off with a fuller ball, angling it away from outside off, at 130.4 clicks. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
We've the first bowling change now. Kyle Jamieson, the number 3 Test bowler in the recent ICC Rankings, gets a chance to roll his arm.
Length ball, outside off. Dean Elgar leans and blocks it out solidly.
Another length ball, angling it in, around middle and leg. Dean Elgar blocks it towards the leg side.
On a length, around off. Dean Elgar blocks it out watchfully.
Much better from Southee now! Length ball, this one shapes in a tad, outside off. Dean Elgar tries to defend this but gets beaten as the ball zips past the outside edge.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Tim Southee serves a shorter delivery now, around off. Dean Elgar picks up the length and pulls it past mid-wicket for a boundary.
Length ball, an inswinger, around middle and leg. Dean Elgar taps it towards mid-wicket.
Good-length delivery, firing it on the pads. Dean Elgar flicks it towards fine leg for a single. He retains the strike!

30 minutes of play negated without any loss of wickets and that's a good start for South Africa after opting to bat. The pitch looked nonresponsive initially but with the sun coming down hard, it is offering more pace and movement.
Matt Henry serves a length ball, from 'round the wicket, nipping back in, outside off. Dean Elgar offers no shot on that.
On a length, shaping away a tad, outside off. Dean Elgar shoulders his arms at it.
Leg Bye! Shorter now, down the leg side. Sarel Erwee looks to tuck this away, but the ball deflects off his pads and goes towards fine leg. A leg bye is taken!
Another length ball, around off. Sarel Erwee defends it out.
Good-length delivery, around middle. Sarel Erwee blocks it out solidly.
Length ball, outside off. Dean Elgar leaves it alone. End of a probing over from Tim Southee!
Beaten! Tad shorter, outside off, this one comes in a bit late. Dean Elgar presses forward and looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
EDGED...but does not carry! Much straighter from Tim Southee now! On a length, outside off. Dean Elgar looks to block this, but gets an outside edge towards first slip, who collects it on a bounce!
Good-length delivery, angling it in, around off. Dean Elgar blocks it out.
On a length now, wide of off. Dean Elgar offers no shot to that.
Back of a length, nipping back in, outside off. Dean Elgar shoulders his arms at it. Good movement there for Tim Southee!
Tad fuller now, around middle, Sarel Erwee leans and blocks it out.
On a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee leans and blocks it towards cover.
Back of a length, shaping away, outside off. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
Good-length delivery, angling it in on the pads. Dean Elgar tucks it towards square leg. Single taken!
Back of a length, outside off. Sarel Erwee looks to defend this, but he gets an inside edge towards fine leg, for a single.
Good-length delivery, nipping back in, outside off. Dean Elgar leans and taps it towards covers and rotates the strike.
Fuller now, outside off. Dean Elgar presses forward and drives it past cover for a single.
Beauty! Length ball, swinging away, outside off. Dean Elgar looks to defend this but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Tim Southee goes shorter now, around off, Dean Elgar is hurried up by the extra bounce and mistimes his pull shot to square leg.
Length ball, shaping back in, outside off. Dean Elgar presses forward and defends it out.

Seems our observation was not correct! This one has moved back in a long way off the pitch. From 'round the wicket, Southee hurls across a length ball outside off. Elgar leaves it on merit but the ball nips back in sharply and goes very closely past the off pole. It kept on moving on its way to the keeper who collects it by stretching to his right.
Tim Southee goes 'round the wicket as well, and serves a fuller one, angling it on middle, Dean Elgar taps it towards mid-wicket.
Lenght ball, around middle, Sarel Erwee pushes it towards mid on.

Early observation! There isn't much seam movement for the Kiwis although there is some good bounce and carry. The South African openers have not been troubled at all so far. The New Zealand bowlers have already switched to 'round the wicket angles, trying out different things.
Length ball, nipping back in, around off. Sarel Erwee leaves it, but gets hit on his thigh pads.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Sarel Erwee leans and blocks it out.
Much fuller now, on the pads. Sarel Erwee uses his wrist and flicks it past square leg for a couple of runs.
Another delivery on a back of a length, outside off, at 135.3 clicks. Sarel Erwee lets that go through.
Matt Henry goes 'round the wicket, serves a shorter ball, outside off. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
Back of a length, outside off. Dean Elgar stays in his crease and taps it towards gully.
Fuller now, angling it in on the pads. Dean Elgar taps it towards mid-wicket. Kyle Jamieson there dives to his left and makes a good stop.
Length delivery, around off. Dean Elgar leans and defends it out.
Good-length delivery, outside off, at 133.2 clicks. Dean Elgar shoulders his arms at it.
Yorker-length delivery, outside off. Dean Elgar digs it out.
Fuller ball now, wide of off. Dean Elgar leans and lets that go through.
Back of a length, around middle, Sarel Erwee blocks it out.
Shorter again, outside off, angling it away. Sarel Erwee offers no shot on that.
Fraction short, this one nips back in, around off, at 137 clicks. Sarel Erwee lets that go through.
Back of a length, outside off, swinging away. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
Length ball, around middle, at 135.3 clicks. Sarel Erwee stays in his crease and defends it out.
Matt Henry starts with a shorter ball, around middle, Sarel Erwee hops and pushes it towards square leg for a brace. Sarel Erwee opens his account!
Matt Henry, who picked up 9 wickets in the first Test, will share the new ball from the opposite end.
Length ball, outside off. Dean Elgar shoulders his arms at it. 4 runs off the first over!
On a length, around middle and leg. Dean Elgar tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Length ball, outside off, shaping back in. Dean Elgar leaves it alone.
Good-length delivery, swinging away, on the pads. Dean Elgar blocks it out.
Tad fuller, around middle, Dean Elgar presents the full face of the bat and defends it out.

FOUR! What a start for Dean Elgar! Tim Southee starts with a length ball, angling it on the pads. Dean Elgar flicks it towards fine leg for a boundary! Dean Elgar and South Africa are underway in style!

It's time to get going now! The players of New Zealand are spreading on the field. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee are the openers for South Africa. Tim Southee, the leading wicket-taker in Tests in New Zealand, is getting ready to bowl. The players take a knee to support the Black Lives Matter movement and here we go...

Right then, a brave decision from Dean Elgar to bat first! The pitch is not as green as the last Test but still, as per the groundsmen, there will be moisture early on and the batting won't be easy. With the sun out in its full glory, it could be a matter of seeing off the initial phase. Do South Africa have it in them to survive the new ball this time? We will find out soon. For now, both teams have come out for their respective national anthems.

New Zealand (Unchanged Playing XI) - Tom Latham (C), Will Young, Devon Conway, Henry Nicholls, Daryl Mitchell, Tom Blundell (WK), Colin de Grandhomme, Kyle Jamieson, Tim Southee, Neil Wagner, Matt Henry.

South Africa (Playing XI) - Dean Elgar (C), Sarel Erwee, Aiden Markram, Rassie van der Dussen, Temba Bavuma, Kyle Verreynne (WK), Wiaan Mulder (In for Zubayr Hamza), Keshav Maharaj (In for Glenton Stuurman), Marco Jansen, Kagiso Rabada, Lutho Sipamla (In for Duanne Olivier).
TOSS - South Africa have won the toss and they have elected to BAT first.

The Proteas came into this series after a thumping win over India, they would have thought they would carry the momentum here as well. But things did not go as planned for Dean Elgar and his men. They were handed a big defeat in the previous game and would like to change things. We might see some changes in the bowling attack for the second game and some changes in their batting as well. South Africa have a lot of quality in their ranks and are well and truly capable of coming out on top. An exciting day of cricket awaits. Stay tuned for the toss and team news.

New Zealand were without their best players, Kane Williamson and Trent Boult but they still managed to outplay South Africa in every department. They won’t be a part of the second Test as well, but that does not seem to be a problem for the Kiwis. Matt Henry was given a chance in the previous game, and he grabbed the opportunity with both hands by giving a Man of the Match performance. New Zealand will be looking to carry the same momentum forward and will be eyeing their maiden Test series win over South Africa.

Hello and a warm welcome, folks! It’s time for the second Test between South Africa and New Zealand to get underway! The hosts put on a dominant show in the first Test and will be coming into this game high on confidence. While South Africa failed to display their true potential and coming into this game they will be hoping to avoid losing their first Test series against New Zealand.
... SECOND TEST ...

We are back for South Africa's second innings! New Zealand players are in a huddle and they now disperse to take their respective fielding positions. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee, the two openers for South Africa are at the crease as well. Tim Southee to start with the ball for New Zealand. Sarel Erwee will face the first ball. Here we go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

New Zealand would be disappointed with the way they have batted here. Their top order didn't fire and it was only because of the partnership between Daryl Mitchell and Colin de Grandhomme that they are still in this game. South Africa's bowlers have done a good job and they would be delighted, Kagiso Rabada registered yet another five-wicket haul and he was sensational along with Marco Jansen. Wiaan Mulder and Lutho Sipamla weren't at their best but it was their spinner, Keshav Maharaj who extracted some turn off the surface and kept the Kiwi batters on their toes. South Africa will now look to pile on some runs on Day 3 and take the game away from the hosts.

So South Africa get a handy lead of 71 runs in the first innings. If not for Colin de Grandhomme and Daryl Mitchell, New Zealand would have been in a deeper hole. South Africa have done well after the Lunch to wrap things up. Neil Wagner was trying to spoil their party but they have made sure that New Zealand stay away from their first innings score.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another wicket and New Zealand have been bowled out! Kagiso Rabada gets a five-wicket haul! Short and outside off. Henry cuts this and doesn't bother to keep it on the ground. The ball travels straight to Rassie van der Dussen at deep point and he takes a good catch. So Rabada comes into the attack and finishes things quickly for his team and Colin de Grandhomme has been left stranded on the non-striker's end. New Zealand have been bowled out for 293 in the first innings!
Commentary.Howout: c Rassie van der Dussen b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: Matt Henry is the last man in.

OUT! TAKEN! Kagiso Rabada gets rid of Wagner with a short ball and South Africa have a wicket just before the second new ball was due! Rabada bangs this short around leg. Wagner pulls it and pulls it quite well actually but finds Marco Jansen at fine leg. He takes a good catch and New Zealand are nine down now. South Africa needed this breakthrough as Wagner was eating up the deficit quite quickly.
Commentary.Howout: c Marco Jansen b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, around leg. Wagner looks to work it towards the leg side but misses.
A short delivery around leg. Wagner looks to pull it but misses.
On a length, on off. Colin de Grandhomme dabs it towards the off side and sets off for a single. The fielder runs in and has a shy at the batter's end  but misses. A risky single taken.
A fuller delivery outside off. Colin de Grandhomme drives it through covers. The fielder in the deep cuts it off as he runs to his right and slides to stop the ball. The batters run two.
Kagiso Rabada comes back into the attack.
Another short delivery on middle. Colin de Grandhomme just pulls it towards square leg for a single.
Back of a length, around leg. Wagner works it towards backward square leg for a single.
Back of a length, around leg. Wagner looks to tuck it away but misses.
FOUR! Neil Wagner is showing everyone how to play a short ball! A short delivery on middle. Wagner backs away and just steers it over the slip cordon for a boundary.
On a length, on middle. Colin de Grandhomme works it to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length, on off. Colin de Grandhomme goes back and blocks it out.
A flatter delivery on middle. Wagner works it towards mid-wicket now.
SIX! Wagner is taking on South African bowlers now! Tossed up delivery on off. Wagner skips down the track and tonks it over long off for a biggie.
A fuller delivery on middle. Wagner works it towards the leg side.
FOUR! Another cracking shot from Wagner! Short and wide outside off. Wagner rocks back and cuts it through point for a boundary.
A fuller delivery on middle. Colin de Grandhomme pushes it to long on for a single.
Tossed up on middle. Colin de Grandhomme blocks it off the front foot.
Another shorter delivery on off. Wagner defends it awkwardly square off the wicket on the off side now.
FOUR! SHOT! This time he connects quite well. A short delivery on off. Wagner hangs on the back foot and pulls it to backward square leg for a boundary.
Jansen goes short again on middle. Wagner decides to go for the pull shot this time. He, however, does not connect it properly and the ball goes in the air towards deep mid-wicket for a couple.
Another shorter delivery around leg. Wagner manages to tuck it towards backwards square leg.
Jansen goes short from 'round the wicket on the body. Wagner ducks under it.
On a length, on middle. Colin de Grandhomme tucks it to fine leg for a single.
Beaten this time! Quicker and around off. Wagner looks to defend it but the ball beats the outside edge of his blade.
Another flatter delivery on off. Wagner blocks it out.
Flatter and shorter on off. Wagner punches it to covers.
Shorter length this time on off. Colin de Grandhomme punches it to covers for a single.
Tossed up around leg. Colin de Grandhomme sweeps it to fine leg for a couple.
A flatter delivery on middle. Colin de Grandhomme works it to mid-wicket.
Jansen continues with the short stuff. It is on off. Colin de Grandhomme gets across and pulls it aerially towards fine leg, just short of the fielder for a single.
SIX! This time he connects and this one sails over the fence! Another short delivery on off. Colin de Grandhomme is expecting it and gets across to pull it over fine leg for a maximum.
A short ball, down leg. Colin de Grandhomme looks to pull but he misses.
Neil Wagner walks out to bat.

OUT! TAKEN! Poor batting by Tim Southee! New Zealand would have been expecting more sensible cricket from their senior player. Jansen bangs this short again on off. Tim Southee again goes for the pull shot but miscues it completely. The ball goes in the air towards mid-wicket and Temba Bavuma takes an easy catch. South Africa get early wicket and New Zealand are now eight down.
Commentary.Howout: c Temba Bavuma b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: Shorter length this time on off. Tim Southee pulls but is hurried by this short ball. It goes towards mid on and the batters run couple.
Jansen starts with a length delivery on off. Tim Southee blocks it out onto the turf.

We are back for the second session and so are the players on the field! Tim Southee and Colin de Grandhomme are at the crease. Marco Jansen will start with the ball after the Lunch break. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

South Africa didn't start that well with the ball on Day 3 and their bowlers weren't consistent enough. Marco Jansen was the pick of the bowlers along with Keshav Maharaj who troubled the well-set Colin de Grandhomme for a majority of the innings. Both these bowlers got one wicket apiece but the tourists must now ensure that they wrap the tail quickly so that they get a handy first innings lead. Colin de Grandhomme was dropped on 101 by Kyle Verreynne and that could prove to be a costly miss if South Africa do not get him early after Lunch. Do join us for the second session which begins at 6.10 am IST (12.40 am GMT).

Colin de Grandhomme and Daryl Mitchell started the day well for the Kiwis as the pair looked quite comfortable in the middle and they also scored at a brisk rate. Mitchell did get out on 60 but the pair added 67 crucial runs in the first session on Day 3. Kyle Jamieson played the supporting role to Colin de Grandhomme who was scoring quite freely. But he too perished just at the stroke of Lunch. The Kiwis would now hope that Colin de Grandhomme bats deeper and they cut down the deficit as early as possible. Although, they have a long way to go but not to forget that New Zealand's lower order batters can contribute.

Yes, New Zealand did lose a couple of wickets in the latter half of the session but still a session that goes their way, thanks to the hard-hitting Colin de Grandhomme who notched up his second Test hundred. A total of 96 runs were scored in the session with the loss of two wickets and New Zealand now trail by 111 runs.

Ohh...what a shot to play on the last ball of the session! Keshav Maharaj serves this slower and on middle and leg. Colin de Grandhomme dances down the track and looks to heave it away but misses and the ball hits his pads. Luckily no damage done and all smiles around as the players go for the Lunch. New Zealand are 253/7 at Lunch on Day 3.
An arm delivery this time. Tim Southee looks to defend but gets the inside half of his blade to backward square leg for a single.
Slower and fuller this time on off. Tim Southee blocks this off the front foot now.
Shorter and flatter on off. Tim Southee goes back and blocks it out.
Darted on the pads. Tim Southee works it towards fine leg and gets a couple.
Tosses it up, on off. Colin de Grandhomme drives it down the ground and takes a single.
A short ball, on off. Tim Southee keeps it out.
Tim Southee walks out to bat.

OUT! TAKEN! So the ploy to bowl short works for South Africa and New Zealand lose another one! Shorter delivery angling into the body from over the wicket now. Kyle Jamieson plays it awkwardly towards leg gully and falls right into the trap. Wiaan Mulder takes a good catch and South Africa get their second wicket of the morning right at the stroke of the Lunch. Kyle Jamieson never looked comfortable against the short ball and walka back now with another disappointing performance with the bat.
Commentary.Howout: c Wiaan Mulder b Marco Jansen
